{"id":"1709.06612","submitter":"Idris Mercer","authors":"Idris Mercer","title":"Finite searches, Chowla's cosine problem, and large Newman polynomials","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A length $n$ cosine sum is an expression of the form $\\cos a_1\\theta + \\cdots\n+ \\cos a_n\\theta$ where $a_1 < \\cdots < a_n$ are positive integers, and a\nlength $n$ Newman polynomial is an expression of the form $z^{a_1} + \\cdots +\nz^{a_n}$ where $a_1 < \\cdots < a_n$ are nonnegative integers. We define\n$-\\lambda(n)$ to be the largest minimum of a length $n$ cosine sum as\n$\\{a_1,\\ldots,a_n\\}$ ranges over all sets of $n$ positive integers, and we\ndefine $\\mu(n)$ to be the largest minimum modulus on the unit circle of a\nlength $n$ Newman polynomial as $\\{a_1,\\ldots,a_n\\}$ ranges over all sets of\n$n$ nonnegative integers. Since there are infinitely many possibilities for the\n$a_j$, it is not obvious how to compute $\\lambda(n)$ or $\\mu(n)$ for a given\n$n$ in finitely many steps. Campbell et al. found the value of $\\mu(3)$ in\n1983, and Goddard found the value of $\\mu(4)$ in 1992. In this paper, we find\nthe values of $\\lambda(2)$ and $\\lambda(3)$ and nontrivial bounds on $\\mu(5)$.\nWe also include further remarks on the seemingly difficult general task of\nreducing the computation of $\\lambda(n)$ or $\\mu(n)$ to a finite problem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 19 Sep 2017 19:08:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-09-21"}
